{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_jerome_ver02/data/77618337/00414188199/1946030401/1374.xml":{"full_text":"32\nIn the Hopper\nMitt, Earmark* $5 Million\nFor Country Road Fund\nGov. Thomas L. Bailey last week\nsigned into Mississippi law a bill\nappropriating $5 million of general\nrevenue to the state highway fund\nto be expended for constructing\nand improving farm to market\nroads.\nThe appropriation is in addition\nto Mississippi's contemplated S6O\nmillion to S7O million postwar high\nway construction program.\n\nWay* to Meet Vet y Ilona*\nStudied by Rhode Itland\nA four-point tax program to fi\nnance a proposed S2O million vet\nerans\u2019 bonus and avert an antici\npated deficit during the next fiscal\nyear, was recommended last week\nby the Rhode Island Tax Study\ncommission. One of the major pro\nposals is based upon enactment of\nan unemployment compensation\nmerit rating bill. The commission\nrecommended that a \u201cbonus pay\nroll tax\u201d equal to 80 percent of\nMONROES SMOOTH THE ROAD TO\nihi nni\nuw^pmmmmmmmm\nH\nMONROE AUTO EQUIPMENT CO MONROE/ MICH.\nthis proposed saving be imposed on\ncorporations to produce $2 million\nfor amortization of proposed sol\ndier bonus bonds.\nIt also proposed that the state\nenact an excise tax on corporations.\nAn increased state tax on pari-mu\ntuel betting from 4 to 5 percent\nwas recommended. The commission\nfurther suggested that the state\nmake permanent its present emer\ngency tax of of 1 percent of\ngross receipts of utilities from the\nsale of electricity, and the addi\ntional $1 per SI,OOO tax on corpo\nrate excess which normally is a\n$4 tax.\n\nCalif. Legislature OK'*\nDisability Payment*\nCalifornia's legislature last week\ngave final approval to a bill under\nwhich California workers who\ncome under the state unemploy\nment insurance system also will\nbe entitled to benefit payments\nwhen illness or disabilities not sub\nject to workmen\u2019s compensation in-\nAUTOMOTIVE NEWS, MARCH 4, 1946\nsuranee prevent them from going\nto their jobs.\nUnder it* terms, unemployment\nbecause of sickness, as in the case\nof economic unemployment, will\nmake an employe eligible for a\nmaximum of S2O a week. A worker\ncould draw either disability or un\nemployment insurance benefits for\n23 weeks in any given year, or 35\nweeks as a maximum for a combi\nnation of the two typos of payment.\nScheduled to start a year after the\nlaw\u2019s enactment, the sickness bene\nfits will be financed entirely out of\nthe present 1 percent paycheck\ncontribution of employes to the\nstate unemployment compensation\nfund.\n\nCut in Speed Limit*\nA\u00bbked in Fa. BUI\nA highway speed limit bill to re\nplace the wartime speed regulation\nact which will expire July 1 has\nbeen introduced in the Virginia\nHouse of Delegates. It seeks a top\nlimit of 5Q miles per hour for cars,\nbuses and trucks.\nFor night driving, between a\nhalf-hour after sunset and a half\nhour before sunrise, it would im\npose a limit of 45 miles per hour\nStyle sells cars; hut it is riding quality and performance\nthat bring repeat orders.\nSpecify Monroe Direct Double Action Hydraulic\nShock absorbers for cars now on your drafting boards\nand smooth the road for sales when competitive going\ngets tough.\nThe new Monroes incorporate many advances made\nin the years of war application. With tripled manufactur\ning facilities, Monroe offers an assured source of supply\nin a wide range of sizes and capacities. Experienced\nMonroe engineers are at your service for immediate\nconsultation and collaboration. Write or wire today.\nMONROE\nNew Direct-Double-Action\nHydraulic Shock Absorbers\nfor private cars and passenger bus\nes and 40 miles for trucks. School\nbuses, limited to 35 miles per hour\nin the daytime, would be cut to 30\nmiles per hour at night. The pres\nent speed law, fixed by wartime\nGeneral Assembly acts to authorize\nthe governor to adjust speed limits\nbetween 35 and 50 miles an hour,\nwill expire this summer.\n\nWartime Speed Repealer\nSigned by N. Governor\nA bill repealing New Jersey\u2019s\nwartime 35-mile-an-hour speed lim\nit was signed into law last week by\nGov. 'Valter E. Edge.\nAlthough there had been some\nquestion whether the repealer did\nnot cancel the state\u2019s complete set\nof speed regulations, it was under\nstood that the governor had been\nadvised that would not be its effect\nand that the 45-mlle-an-hour top\nlimit that was effective before the\nwar would be restored.\n\nCommercial Rent Lctu\nA\u00bbked for IV. Y. State\nEnactment of a statewide com\nmercial rent control law was urged\nlast week on the New York leg-\nislature by the Joint Action com\nmittee, an organization of 83 traded\ngroups. New York state now has a\nrent control law applying only to\nNew York city.\n\nR. I. Grange Again Plant*\nAnti-Divertion Measure\nThe attempt of the Rhode\nState Grange to obtain an amend\nment to the state constitution re\nstricting the use of revenue\nthe state gasoline tax and motor\nvehicle registration and license fees\nto the construction, reconstruction!\nand maintenance of roads and\nbridges has made its annual ap\npearance in the state legislature.\nThe bill was referred to the spe\ncial legislation committee. This\nas far as previous similar proposals\nhave ever gone.\nKy. Bill Would Allow\nStay* of Operation\nKentucky\u2019s house of representa\ntives recently passed and sent to\nthe state senate a bill to extend'\npowers of the State Motor Trans\nportation division.\nThe bill would allow the division\nto grant stays of operation to per\nmit holders and to allow them to<\nabandon operations temporarily.\nUnder present Kentucky law, those\ngranted operating permits are re- 1\nquired to begin operations within\n60 days after issuance of permits.\n1\nIdaho Studie* Increaae\nIn Highway Fund*\nIdaho state legislature is consid\nering a bill for $300,000 for the state\nhighway patrol, supplementing\nmoneys appropriated at the regular\nsession last January, and extra i\nmoney for the state highway fund.\n\nNon-Use Tax Upheld\nNon-highway users are entitled\nto refunds of a special 1-cent gaso\nline tax enacted by the 1945 Idaho\nlegislature to provide funds for\nmatching with postwar federal\nhighway allotments, the Idaho Su\npreme court ruled unanimously last\nweek in reversing an Ada county\ncourt decision. The opinion held\nthat \u201cthe motor fuels tax is not a\ntax for general purposes, but a\nprivilege tax. A tax exacted from\nthose who use the highways in pro- 1\nportion to the use for the construc\ntion and maintenance of highways.\"\nl\nKentucky Ga* Rebate\nKentucky's Gov. Simeon Willis\nallowed to become law last week,\nwithout his signature, a bill to re\nfund 90 percent of the state tax on\ngasoline used in tractors and sta\ntionary engines on farms. The re\nmaining 10 percent goes for ad\nministration of the refund.\n\nTo Vote on Sale* Tax\nVoters of Panama City, Fla., will\nvote Apr. 16 on a proposal to pay\nfor a $3,500,000 postwar improve\nment program with a general sales\ntax. It is believed that Panama City\nwill be the first Florida city to vote\non such a proposal.\n\nClo*ed Shop Ban Lose*\nA proposal to ban closed shops\nwas unfavorably reported last week\nby the labor committee of the Mis\nsissippi house of representatives. A\nminority report favoring the meas\nure also was filed.\nO Ultra art profltlni from AN Want\nAda. why not you? .Bat Inalda backcover.\nWANTED\nSERVICE MANAGER\nNationally-known manufacturer\nof automotive maintenance\nequipment has opening for man\nto head Service Department.\nMust be experienced In claims\nand adjustments, parts merchan\ndising, management of author\nized service stations, prepara\ntion of service manuals, etc.\nKnowledge of hydraulics pre\nferred. This is real opportunity\nfor right man. Position was held\nopen for previous manager who\nenlisted but did not return.\nWrite giving full details of ex\nperience, positions held and sal\nary expectancy.\nWrite Box AN, c/o Automotive\nNews, Detroit 26, Mich.","height":"18888","width":"13857"}}
